    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-08-17T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-08-17T10:00:00-05:00" n="665"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d665">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">767.68119/8–1746: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-08-17T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 17, 1946—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 17—11 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4078. Secret for Ambassador Wilson<note n="67" xml:id="d665fn67">See last
                        paragraph regarding relay to Ankara.</note> from the Secretary: I think that
                    the Turkish Government would have to express willingness to attend an
                    international conference on the revision of the Montreux Convention. However,
                    if, as indicated in your telegram 871 to Department,<note n="68"
                        xml:id="d665fn68">Not printed.</note> the Turkish Government stated in its
                    acceptance that it could not consider any proposal which would liquidate an
                    international treaty (point 4) which by its terms remains in effect for 10 years
                    more and replace it by a new agreement excluding present signatories of existing
                    treaty (with the exception of Japan), and if the Turkish Government also stated
                    that it could not seriously consider point 5 on grounds that it is a direct
                    threat to Turkish sovereignty and independence, the US Government would
                    understand and sympathize since under similar circumstances we would take the
                    same position. You are authorized to convey the foregoing to the Turkish
                    Government.</p>
                <p>Department please relay to Ankara as 23 from Paris.</p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
